{"title":"Hybrid Inverted Index Is a Robust Accelerator for Dense Retrieval","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Vector-quantization IVF indexes for dense retrieval are lossy: at low latency they often miss relevant documents unless many clusters are probed, which sharply increases runtime.","method":"Hybrid Inverted Index (HI2) organizes two complementary inverted lists per corpus: embedding clusters (semantic) and salient terms (lexical). Each document is indexed to its nearest cluster (via KMeans centroids) and to K_T1 top-scored terms (BM25 or a BERT+MLP scorer). At query time, HI2 dispatches to the top-K_C clusters (by query–centroid similarity) and to K_T2 terms (all tokens if short, otherwise top by precomputed average term score), merges candidates, and evaluates them with PQ/OPQ. This hybrid candidate generation leverages the complementarity of clusters and terms to achieve higher recall at lower latency than IVF and even HNSW while approaching brute-force quality."},{"problem":"Unsupervised cluster/term selection (KMeans, BM25) is strong but not optimal; we need a principled way to learn the hybrid index selectors directly for retrieval effectiveness without sacrificing efficiency.","method":"HI2_sup introduces a joint knowledge distillation objective to train cluster embeddings and the term-scoring network end-to-end against a teacher built from off-the-shelf dense embeddings. It minimizes KL divergence between the teacher’s softmaxed relevance over a sampled document set and (a) the cluster selector’s distribution derived from query–centroid similarities mapped to documents’ assigned clusters, and (b) the term selector’s distribution from query/document term-score vector similarities; a commitment loss keeps document embeddings close to their assigned cluster. This learning substantially boosts recall and approaches the teacher/brute-force effectiveness at low latency."},{"problem":"Selecting salient query terms can add undesirable online cost if it relies on heavy neural processing, yet accurate lexical cues are needed to recover relevant documents missed by clustering.","method":"HI2 makes query-time term selection lightweight by performing all heavy term scoring offline on documents (BM25 or BERT+MLP), storing per-term scores and the global average score per term. At search time, it selects all tokens for short queries and only the top-K_T2 tokens by average score for long queries, avoiding neural computation on queries. This keeps query dispatch overhead negligible while preserving the lexical benefits that improve candidate recall and overall efficiency."}]}
